	title = {A COMPARATIVE STUDY OF ZERO-SHOT MULTIMODAL RETRIEVAL-AUGMENTED GENERATION FOR IMAGE LABELING IN MANUFACTURING: GPT-4O-MINI VS. LLAMA 3.2 VISION},
	year = {2025},
	journal = {Proceedings of the ASME Design Engineering Technical Conference},
	volume = {2-B},
	pages = {},
	doi = {10.1115/DETC2025-169557},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105024202037?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Semantic Computing Lab, School of Manufacturing Systems and Networks, Arizona State University, Mesa, 85212, AZ, United States; Digital Manufacturing and Design Lab, School of Manufacturing Systems and Networks, Arizona State University, Mesa, 85212, AZ, United States},
	abstract = {Image data plays a significant role in manufacturing by enabling visual documentation, quality control, equipment monitoring, and the communication of technological capabilities. In particular, manufacturing companies use images extensively on their website to advertise their capabilites. Consistent efforts have been made to identify, categorize, and label various features associated with manufacturing images, such as products, services, equipment, and processes. In this paper, we introduce a robust pipeline leveraging Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLM) specifically GPT-4o-mini and Llama 3.2 Vision—to enhance zero-shot image labeling accuracy in manufacturing contexts. The pipeline extracts images and associated metadata from manufacturer websites and predicts multiple labels per image, including product identification, equipment names, process capabilities, and industry classifications. Using a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) approach, the methodology integrates external knowledge sources such as metadata descriptions and industry-specific terminology to inform predictions without requiring extensive fine-tuning. Experimental evaluation reveals notable differences in model agreement rates and confidence patterns between the two systems. Both models demonstrated effectiveness in recognizing common product and industry names but faced challenges in more complex categories such as process capabilities and equipment identification. The research highlights critical areas for improvement, including confidence calibration, domain-specific fine-tuning, ensemble methods, and scalability considerations. Despite these challenges, the pipeline establishes a foundation for automated manufacturing image labeling with promising avenues for future enhancements in reliability, efficiency, and domain-specific optimization. This work contributes to advancing intelligent automation in manufacturing by addressing key bottlenecks in multimodal image labeling tasks. © 2025 by ASME.},
	keywords = {Automation; Data communication equipment; Quality control; Tuning; Visual communication; Comparatives studies; Domain specific; Equipment monitoring; Fine tuning; Image data; Image labeling; Multi-modal; Process capabilities; Quality control equipment; Technological capability; Industrial research; Metadata},
