	abstract = {Building on Han et al. [1], we introduce Directed Duo Analysis (DDA), a novel dual-agent system with a vertical structure designed for financial investment analysis. DDA employs a subordinate agent for specialized analysis (fundamentals, market sentiment, or risk) and a leader agent for synthesizing outputs, utilizing tools like Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) and task-specific APIs. Through five experiments on a simulated dataset of 30 Dow Jones companies' 2023 SEC 10K forms and external data, we demonstrate DDA's competitive performance: a Risk Analysis Score of 4.22 (vs. baseline 4.23), Buy/Not Buy Decision Accuracy of 68.3% (vs. baseline 66.7%), and Stock Price Prediction Error of 2.18% (vs. baseline 2.35%). Our findings show that risk-focused roles with strong leadership optimize complex tasks, while mixed roles enhance overall accuracy. DDA improves efficiency by reducing coordination overhead while maintaining high coherence (up to 4.25), offering a scalable framework for accurate and coherent investment recommendations. Future work involves integrating real-time LLMs and broader data sources. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).},
