	affiliations = {Kuwait Oil Company, Kuwait; slb},
	abstract = {Kuwait Oil Company (KOC) drilling operations generate large volumes of technical documentation-including Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs), Non-Productive Time (NPT) reports and Daily Drilling Reports (DDRs), capturing critical operational knowledge. However, these records are often unstructured, dispersed across multiple repositories, and stored in inconsistent formats such as PDFs, scanned images, handwritten notes, and text files. This fragmented landscape makes it difficult for engineers to efficiently locate essential information or apply lessons learned. As a result, decision-making is delayed, operational risk increases, and onboarding of new drilling personnel becomes time-intensive. This paper introduces a Generative AI framework to address these challenges by enhancing institutional knowledge accessibility within KOC. The proposed architecture incorporates Large Language Models (LLMs), Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG), and Optical Character Recognition (OCR) to automate knowledge extraction and contextual retrieval from drilling documentation. Key components include OCR-based ingestion, semantic chunking, multi-scale retrieval, and domain-tuned prompting to ensure responses remain accurate, traceable, and grounded in authenticated operator content. A conversational interface enables engineers to query operational guidance, historical insights, and technical references in real time. Deployment of this system at KOC demonstrated measurable improvements, including reduced document search time, improved procedural adherence, and accelerated onboarding of drilling engineers. The solution is scalable to additional domains such as Geoscientists, production, and reservoir engineering. Overall, this work shows that Generative AI can effectively support safer, faster decision-making and serve as an enabling catalyst in KOC's digital transformation journey. Copyright 2026, Society of Petroleum Engineers.},
