	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033652907?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {School of Computing, Telkom University, Bandung, Indonesia},
	abstract = {The Indonesian legal system comprises interconnected regulatory levels, from the Constitution to internal company regulations. This complexity poses significant challenges in ensuring consistency and compliance with legal hierarchies, particularly when drafting new regulations. Although public access to legal documents is available, the process of tracing and analyzing regulations remains manual and time-consuming, potentially hindering rapid responses to social, economic, and technological changes. This paper presents a question-answering (QA) system based on Knowledge Graph Retrieval-Augmented Generation (KG-RAG) enhanced with an Agentic RAG approach to support the efficiency of corporate legal teams. The system was built through information extraction from public legal documents, knowledge graph construction using Neo4j, semantic embedding using OpenAI models, and storage of embedding results in FAISS for similarity-based search and contextual understanding. LLM agents were employed for data extraction automation, validation, and query processing management with adaptive reasoning capabilities and task orchestration. Evaluation results demonstrate that the system achieves 96% accuracy on direct queries and 80% accuracy on semantic queries, with response times of 2-3 seconds and 4-6 seconds, respectively. The system successfully identifies regulatory relationships and provides relevant and contextual policy recommendations, thereby accelerating the regulation drafting process while maintaining legal accuracy, consistency, and transparency across multiple domains and organizational levels. © 2025 IEEE.},
